re-action Meeting (p. 0), Technology and Construction Court Guide", "8": "2.5, Section 2. Pre-Action Protocol and conduct, 2.4.3 Pre-action Meeting (p. 0), Technology and Construction Court Guide", "9": "2.5, Section 2. Pre-Action Protocol and conduct, 2.4.3 Pre-action Meeting (p. 0), Technology and Construction Court Guide"}, "data_points": {"images": null, "text": [{"category": "Technology and Construction Court", "citation": "2.3, Section 2. Pre-Action Protocol and conduct, 2.3 Exceptions (p. 12), Technology and Construction Court Guide", "content": "2.3.1 A claimant does not have to comply with the Protocol if the claim:

a) is to enforce the decision of an adjudicator;

b) is to seek an urgent declaration or injunction in relation to adjudication (whether ongoing or concluded);

c) includes a claim for interim injunctive relief;

d) will be the subject of a claim for summary judgment pursuant to Part 24 of the CPR; or

e) relates to the same or substantially the same issues as have been the subject of a recent adjudication or some other formal alternative dispute resolution procedure; or

f) relates to a public procurement dispute (for which there is a separate pre-action process as set out in Appendix H).", "filepath": "Section 2. Pre-Action Protocol and conduct, 2.3 Exceptions (p. 12)", "groups": [], "id": "section_2_pre_action_protocol_and_conduct_23_exceptions_p_12_subsection_0", "is_subsection": true, "oids": [], "original_doc_id": "section_2_pre_action_protocol_and_conduct_23_exceptions_p_12", "reranker_score": 2.311666965484619, "score": 0.03128054738044739, "sourcefile": "Technology and Construction Court Guide", "sourcepage": "Section 2. Pre-Action Protocol and conduct, 2.3 Exceptions (p. 12)", "storageUrl": "https://www.judiciary.uk/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/The-Technology-and-Construction-Court-Guide.pdf", "storageurl": "https://www.judiciary.uk/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/The-Technology-and-Construction-Court-Guide.pdf", "subsection_id": "2.3", "subsection_index": 0, "total_subsections": 5, "updated": "2022-10-01T00:00:00Z", "url": "https://www.judiciary.uk/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/The-Technology-and-Construction-Court-Guide.pdf"}, {"category": "Technology and Construction Court", "citation": "2.3, Section 2. Pre-Action Protocol and conduct, 2.3 Exceptions (p. 12), Technology and Construction Court Guide", "content": "2.3.2 In addition, a claimant need not comply with any part of the Protocol if, by so doing, the claim may become time-barred under the Limitation Act 1980. In those circumstances, a claimant should commence proceedings without complying with the Protocol and must, at the same time, apply for directions as to the timetable and form of procedure to be adopted. The Court may order a stay of those proceedings pending completion of the steps set out in the Protocol.", "filepath": "Section 2. Pre-Action Protocol and conduct, 2.3 Exceptions (p. 12)", "groups": [], "id": "section_2_pre_action_protocol_and_conduct_23_exceptions_p_12_subsection_1", "is_subsection": true, "oids": [], "original_doc_id": "section_2_pre_action_protocol_and_conduct_23_exceptions_p_12", "reranker_score": 2.311666965484619, "score": 0.03128054738044739, "sourcefile": "Technology and Construction Court Guide", "sourcepage": "Section 2. Pre-Action Protocol and conduct, 2.4.3 Pre-action Meeting (p. 0)", "storageUrl": "https://www.judiciary.uk/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/The-Technology-and-Construction-Court-Guide.pdf", "storageurl": "https://www.judiciary.uk/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/The-Technology-and-Construction-Court-Guide.pdf", "subsection_id": "2.3", "subsection_index": 1, "total_subsections": 5, "updated": "2022-10-01T00:00:00Z", "url": "https://www.judiciary.uk/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/The-Technology-and-Construction-Court-Guide.pdf"}, {"category": "Civil Procedure Rules and Practice Directions", "citation": "2.4, Section 2. Pre-Action Protocol and conduct, 2.3 Exceptions (p. 12), Technology and Construction Court Guide", "content": "2.4 Essential Ingredients of the Protocol", "filepath": "Section 2. Pre-Action Protocol and conduct, 2.3 Exceptions (p. 12)", "groups": [], "id": "section_2_pre_action_protocol_and_conduct_23_exceptions_p_12_subsection_2", "is_subsection": true, "oids": [], "original_doc_id": "section_2_pre_action_protocol_and_conduct_23_exceptions_p_12", "reranker_score": 2.311666965484619, "score": 0.03128054738044739, "sourcefile": "Practice Direction 18", "sourcepage": "Practice Direction 18", "storageUrl": "https://www.judiciary.uk/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/The-Technology-and-Construction-Court-Guide.pdf", "storageurl": "https://www.justice.gov.uk/courts/procedure-rules/civil/rules/part18/pd_part18", "subsection_id": "2.4", "subsection_index": 2, "total_subsections": 5, "updated": "2017-01-30T00:00:00Z", "url": "https://www.judiciary.uk/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/The-Technology-and-Construction-Court-Guide.pdf"}, {"category": "Technology and Construction Court", "citation": "2.4, Section 2. Pre-Action Protocol and conduct, 2.3 Exceptions (p. 12), Technology and Construction Court Guide", "content": "2.4.1 The Letter of Claim

The letter of claim must comply with Section 3 of the Protocol. Amongst other things, it must contain a clear and concise summary of the facts on which each claim is based; the basis on which each claim is made; and details of the relief claimed, including a breakdown showing how any damages have been quantified. The claimant must also provide the names of experts already instructed and on whom reliance is intended.", "filepath": "Section 2. Pre-Action Protocol and conduct, 2.3 Exceptions (p. 12)", "groups": [], "id": "section_2_pre_action_protocol_and_conduct_23_exceptions_p_12_subsection_3", "is_subsection": true, "oids": [], "original_doc_id": "section_2_pre_action_protocol_and_conduct_23_exceptions_p_12", "reranker_score": 2.311666965484619, "score": 0.03128054738044739, "sourcefile": "Technology and Construction Court Guide", "sourcepage": "Section 2. Pre-Action Protocol and conduct, 2.3 Exceptions (p. 12)", "storageUrl": "https://www.judiciary.uk/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/The-Technology-and-Construction-Court-Guide.pdf", "storageurl": "https://www.judiciary.uk/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/The-Technology-and-Construction-Court-Guide.pdf", "subsection_id": "2.4", "subsection_index": 3, "total_subsections": 5, "updated": "2022-10-01T00:00:00Z", "url": "https://www.judiciary.uk/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/The-Technology-and-Construction-Court-Guide.pdf"}, {"category": "Technology and Construction Court", "citation": "2.4, Section 2. Pre-Action Protocol and conduct, 2.3 Exceptions (p. 12), Technology and Construction Court Guide", "content": "2.4.2 The Defendant's Response

The defendant has 14 days to acknowledge the letter of claim and 28 days (from receipt of the letter of claim) either to take any jurisdictional objection or to respond in substance to the letter of claim. Paragraph 10.1 of the Protocol enables the parties to agree an extension of the 28 day period up to a maximum of 3 months. In any case of substance it is quite usual for an extension of time to be agreed for the defendant's response. The letter of response must comply with paragraph 8 of the Protocol. Amongst other things, it must state which claims are accepted, which claims are rejected and on what basis. It must set out any counterclaim to be advanced by the defendant. The defendant should also provide the names of experts who have been instructed and on whom reliance is intended. If the defendant fails either to acknowledge or to respond to the letter of claim in time, the claimant is entitled to commence proceedings.", "filepath": "Section 2. Pre-Action Protocol and conduct, 2.3 Exceptions (p. 12)", "groups": [], "id": "section_2_pre_action_protocol_and_conduct_23_exceptions_p_12_subsection_4", "is_subsection": true, "oids": [], "original_doc_id": "section_2_pre_action_protocol_and_conduct_23_exceptions_p_12", "reranker_score": 2.311666965484619, "score": 0.03128054738044739, "sourcefile": "Technology and Construction Court Guide", "sourcepage": "Section 2. Pre-Action Protocol and conduct, 2.3 Exceptions (p. 12)", "storageUrl": "https://www.judiciary.uk/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/The-Technology-and-Construction-Court-Guide.pdf", "storageurl": "https://www.judiciary.uk/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/The-Technology-and-Construction-Court-Guide.pdf", "subsection_id": "2.4", "subsection_index": 4, "total_subsections": 5, "updated": "2022-10-01T00:00:00Z", "url": "https://www.judiciary.uk/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/The-Technology-and-Construction-Court-Guide.pdf"}, {"category": "Technology and Construction Court", "citation": "2.4, Section 2. Pre-Action Protocol and conduct, 2.4.3 Pre-action Meeting (p. 0), Technology and Construction Court Guide", "content": "2.4.4 Proportionality

The Protocol does not contemplate an extended process and it should not be used as a tool of oppression. Thus, the letter of claim should be concise and it is usually sufficient to explain the proposed claim(s), identifying key dates, so as to enable the potential defendant to understand and to investigate the allegations. Only essential documents need be supplied, and the period specified for a response should not be longer than one month without good reason. In particular, where a claim is brought by a litigant based outside the UK it will generally be appropriate to confine the steps to the time limits provided by the Protocol and, in many cases, to dispense with the meeting referred to in paragraph 5.1 of the Protocol. In any event, such a meeting is not mandatory and may be dispensed with if it would involve disproportionate time and cost or it is clear that it would be unlikely to serve any useful purpose.", "filepath": "Section 2. Pre-Action Protocol and conduct, 2.4.3 Pre-action Meeting (p. 0)", "groups": [], "id": "section_2_pre_action_protocol_and_conduct_243_pre_action_meeting_p_0_subsection_0", "is_subsection": true, "oids": [], "original_doc_id": "section_2_pre_action_protocol_and_conduct_243_pre_action_meeting_p_0", "reranker_score": 2.2603132724761963, "score": 0.01587301678955555, "sourcefile": "Technology and Construction Court Guide", "sourcepage": "Section 2. Pre-Action Protocol and conduct, 2.4.3 Pre-action Meeting (p. 0)", "storageUrl": "https://www.judiciary.uk/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/The-Technology-and-Construction-Court-Guide.pdf", "storageurl": "https://www.judiciary.uk/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/The-Technology-and-Construction-Court-Guide.pdf", "subsection_id": "2.4", "subsection_index": 0, "total_subsections": 4, "updated": "2022-10-01T00:00:00Z", "url": "https://www.judiciary.uk/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/The-Technology-and-Construction-Court-Guide.pdf"}, {"category": "Technology and Construction Court", "citation": "2.5, Section 2. Pre-Action Protocol and conduct, 2.4.3 Pre-action Meeting (p. 0), Technology and Construction Court Guide", "content": "2.5 Use of Material Generated by the Protocol", "filepath": "Section 2. Pre-Action Protocol and conduct, 2.4.3 Pre-action Meeting (p. 0)", "groups": [], "id": "section_2_pre_action_protocol_and_conduct_243_pre_action_meeting_p_0_subsection_1", "is_subsection": true, "oids": [], "original_doc_id": "section_2_pre_action_protocol_and_conduct_243_pre_action_meeting_p_0", "reranker_score": 2.2603132724761963, "score": 0.01587301678955555, "sourcefile": "Technology and Construction Court Guide", "sourcepage": "Section 2. Pre-Action Protocol and conduct, 2.4.3 Pre-action Meeting (p. 0)", "storageUrl": "https://www.judiciary.uk/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/The-Technology-and-Construction-Court-Guide.pdf", "storageurl": "https://www.judiciary.uk/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/The-Technology-and-Construction-Court-Guide.pdf", "subsection_id": "2.5", "subsection_index": 1, "total_subsections": 4, "updated": "2022-10-01T00:00:00Z", "url": "https://www.judiciary.uk/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/The-Technology-and-Construction-Court-Guide.pdf"}, {"category": "Technology and Construction Court", "citation": "2.5, Section 2. Pre-Action Protocol and conduct, 2.4.3 Pre-action Meeting (p. 0), Technology and Construction Court Guide", "content": "2.5.1 The letter of claim, the defendant's response, and the information relating to attendance (or otherwise) at the meeting are not confidential or 'without prejudice' and can therefore be referred to by the parties in any subsequent litigation. The detail of any discussion at the meeting(s) and/or any note of the meeting cannot be referred to the Court unless all parties agree.", "filepath": "Section 2. Pre-Action Protocol and conduct, 2.4.3 Pre-action Meeting (p. 0)", "groups": [], "id": "section_2_pre_action_protocol_and_conduct_243_pre_action_meeting_p_0_subsection_2", "is_subsection": true, "oids": [], "original_doc_id": "section_2_pre_action_protocol_and_conduct_243_pre_action_meeting_p_0", "reranker_score": 2.2603132724761963, "score": 0.01587301678955555, "sourcefile": "Technology and Construction Court Guide", "sourcepage": "Section 2. Pre-Action Protocol and conduct, 2.4.3 Pre-action Meeting (p. 0)", "storageUrl": "https://www.judiciary.uk/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/The-Technology-and-Construction-Court-Guide.pdf", "storageurl": "https://www.judiciary.uk/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/The-Technology-and-Construction-Court-Guide.pdf", "subsection_id": "2.5", "subsection_index": 2, "total_subsections": 4, "updated": "2022-10-01T00:00:00Z", "url": "https://www.judiciary.uk/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/The-Technology-and-Construction-Court-Guide.pdf"}, {"category": "Technology and Construction Court", "citation": "2.5, Section 2. Pre-Action Protocol and conduct, 2.4.3 Pre-action Meeting (p. 0), Technology and Construction Court Guide", "content": "2.5.2 Normally the parties should include in the bundle for the first case management conference: (a) the letter of claim, (b) the response, and (c) if the parties agree, any agreed note of the pre-action meeting: see Section 5 below. The documents attached to or enclosed with the letter and the response should not be included in the bundle.", "filepath": "Section 2. Pre-Action Protocol and conduct, 2.4.3 Pre-action Meeting (p. 0)", "groups": [], "id": "section_2_pre_action_protocol_and_conduct_243_pre_action_meeting_p_0_subsection_3", "is_subsection": true, "oids": [], "original_doc_id": "section_2_pre_action_protocol_and_conduct_243_pre_action_meeting_p_0", "reranker_score": 2.2603132724761963, "score": 0.01587301678955555, "sourcefile": "Technology and Construction Court Guide", "sourcepage": "Section 2. Pre-Action Protocol and conduct, 2.4.3 Pre-action Meeting (p. 0)", "storageUrl": "https://www.judiciary.uk/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/The-Technology-and-Construction-Court-Guide.pdf", "storageurl": "https://www.judiciary.uk/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/The-Technology-and-Construction-Court-Guide.pdf", "subsection_id": "2.5", "subsection_index": 3, "total_subsections": 4, "updated": "2022-10-01T00:00:00Z", "url": "https://www.judiciary.uk/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/The-Technology-and-Construction-Court-Guide.pdf"}, {"category": "Civil Procedure Rules and Practice Directions", "citation": "1.1, Practice Direction 18, Practice Direction 18", "content": "1.1 Before making an application to the court for an order under Part 18, the party seeking clarification or information (the first party) should first serve on the party from whom it is sought (the second party) a written request for that clarification or information (a Request) stating a date by which the response to the Request should be served. The date must allow the second party a reasonable time to respond.", "filepath": "Practice Direction 18", "groups": [], "id": "Practice_Direction_18_subsection_0", "is_subsection": true, "oids": [], "original_doc_id": "Practice_Direction_18", "reranker_score": 2.224733352661133, "score": 0.026545699685811996, "sourcefile": "Practice Direction 18", "sourcepage": "Practice Direction 18", "storageUrl": "https://www.justice.gov.uk/courts/procedure-rules/civil/rules/part18/pd_part18", "storageurl": "https://www.justice.gov.uk/courts/procedure-rules/civil/rules/part18/pd_part18", "subsection_id": "1.1", "subsection_index": 0, "total_subsections": 21, "updated": "2017-01-30T00:00:00Z", "url": "https://www.justice.gov.uk/courts/procedure-rules/civil/rules/part18/pd_part18"}, {"category": "Civil Procedure Rules and Practice Directions", "citation": "1.2, Practice Direction 18, Practice Direction 18", "content": "1.2 A Request should be concise and strictly confined to matters which are reasonably necessary and proportionate to enable the first party to prepare his own case or to understand the case he has to meet.", "filepath": "Practice Direction 18", "groups": [], "id": "Practice_Direction_18_subsection_1", "is_subsection": true, "oids": [], "original_doc_id": "Practice_Direction_18", "reranker_score": 2.224733352661133, "score": 0.026545699685811996, "sourcefile": "Practice Direction 18", "sourcepage": "Practice Direction 18", "storageUrl": "https://www.justice.gov.uk/courts/procedure-rules/civil/rules/part18/pd_part18", "storageurl": "https://www.justice.gov.uk/courts/procedure-rules/civil/rules/part18/pd_part18", "subsection_id": "1.2", "subsection_index": 1, "total_subsections": 21, "updated": "2017-01-30T00:00:00Z", "url": "https://www.justice.gov.uk/courts/procedure-rules/civil/rules/part18/pd_part18"}, {"category": "Civil Procedure Rules and Practice Directions", "citation": "1.3, Practice Direction 18, Practice Direction 18", "content": "1.3 Requests must be made as far as possible in a single comprehensive document and not piecemeal.", "filepath": "Practice Direction 18", "groups": [], "id": "Practice_Direction_18_subsection_2", "is_subsection": true, "oids": [], "original_doc_id": "Practice_Direction_18", "reranker_score": 2.224733352661133, "score": 0.026545699685811996, "sourcefile": "Practice Direction 18", "sourcepage": "Practice Direction 18", "storageUrl": "https://www.justice.gov.uk/courts/procedure-rules/civil/rules/part18/pd_part18", "storageurl": "https://www.justice.gov.uk/courts/procedure-rules/civil/rules/part18/pd_part18", "subsection_id": "1.3", "subsection_index": 2, "total_subsections": 21, "updated": "2017-01-30T00:00:00Z", "url": "https://www.justice.gov.uk/courts/procedure-rules/civil/rules/part18/pd_part18"}, {"category": "Civil Procedure Rules and Practice Directions", "citation": "1.4, Practice Direction 18, Practice Direction 18", "content": "1.4 A Request may be made by letter if the text of the Request is brief and the reply is likely to be brief; otherwise the Request should be made in a separate document.", "filepath": "Practice Direction 18", "groups": [], "id": "Practice_Direction_18_subsection_3", "is_subsection": true, "oids": [], "original_doc_id": "Practice_Direction_18", "reranker_score": 2.224733352661133, "score": 0.026545699685811996, "sourcefile": "Practice Direction 18", "sourcepage": "Practice Direction 18", "storageUrl": "https://www.justice.gov.uk/courts/procedure-rules/civil/rules/part18/pd_part18", "storageurl": "https://www.justice.gov.uk/courts/procedure-rules/civil/rules/part18/pd_part18", "subsection_id": "1.4", "subsection_index": 3, "total_subsections": 21, "updated": "2017-01-30T00:00:00Z", "url": "https://www.justice.gov.uk/courts/procedure-rules/civil/rules/part18/pd_part18"}, {"category": "Civil Procedure Rules and Practice Directions", "citation": "1.5, Practice Direction 18, Practice Direction 18", "content": "1.5 If a Request is made in a letter, the letter should, in order to distinguish it from any other that might routinely be written in the course of a case,

(1) state that it contains a Request made under Part 18, and

(2) deal with no matters other than the Request.", "filepath": "Practice Direction 18", "groups": [], "id": "Practice_Direction_18_subsection_4", "is_subsection": true, "oids": [], "original_doc_id": "Practice_Direction_18", "reranker_score": 2.224733352661133, "score": 0.026545699685811996, "sourcefile": "Practice Direction 18", "sourcepage": "Practice Direction 18", "storageUrl": "https://www.justice.gov.uk/courts/procedure-rules/civil/rules/part18/pd_part18", "storageurl": "https://www.justice.gov.uk/courts/procedure-rules/civil/rules/part18/pd_part18", "subsection_id": "1.5", "subsection_index": 4, "total_subsections": 21, "updated": "2017-01-30T00:00:00Z", "url": "https://www.justice.gov.uk/courts/procedure-rules/civil/rules/part18/pd_part18"}, {"category": "Civil Procedure Rules and Practice Directions", "citation": "1.6, Practice Direction 18, Practice Direction 18", "content": "1.6

(1) A Request (whether made by letter or in a separate document) must -

(a) be headed with the name of the court and the title and number of the claim,

(b) in its heading state that it is a Request made under Part 18, identify the first party and the second party and state the date on which it is made,

(c) set out in a separate numbered paragraph each request for information or clarification,

(d) where a Request relates to a document, identify that document and (if relevant) the paragraph or words to which it relates,

(e) state the date by which the first party expects a response to the Request.

(2)

(a) A Request which is not in the form of a letter may, if convenient, be prepared in such a way that the response may be given on the same document.

(b) To do this the numbered paragraphs of the Request should appear on the left hand half of each sheet so that the paragraphs of the response may then appear on the right.

(c) Where a Request is prepared in this form an extra copy should be served for the use of the second party.", "filepath": "Practice Direction 18", "groups": [], "id": "Practice_Direction_18_subsection_5", "is_subsection": true, "oids": [], "original_doc_id": "Practice_Direction_18", "reranker_score": 2.224733352661133, "score": 0.026545699685811996, "sourcefile": "Practice Direction 18", "sourcepage": "Practice Direction 18", "storageUrl": "https://www.justice.gov.uk/courts/procedure-rules/civil/rules/part18/pd_part18", "storageurl": "https://www.justice.gov.uk/courts/procedure-rules/civil/rules/part18/pd_part18", "subsection_id": "1.6", "subsection_index": 5, "total_subsections": 21, "updated": "2017-01-30T00:00:00Z", "url": "https://www.justice.gov.uk/courts/procedure-rules/civil/rules/part18/pd_part18"}, {"category": "Civil Procedure Rules and Practice Directions", "citation": "1.7, Practice Direction 18, Practice Direction 18", "content": "1.7 Subject to the provisions of rule 6.23(5) and (6) and paragraphs 4.1 to 4.3 of Practice Direction 6 A, a request should be served by e-mail if reasonably practicable.

