Duty of search", "filepath": "Disclosure and Inspection of Documents", "groups": [], "id": "Part_31___Disclosure_and_Inspection_of_Documents_subsection_5", "is_subsection": true, "oids": [], "original_doc_id": "Part_31___Disclosure_and_Inspection_of_Documents", "reranker_score": 2.61181378364563, "score": 0.02460360899567604, "sourcefile": "Part 31", "sourcepage": "Disclosure and Inspection of Documents", "storageUrl": "https://www.justice.gov.uk/courts/procedure-rules/civil/rules/part31", "storageurl": "https://www.justice.gov.uk/courts/procedure-rules/civil/rules/part31", "subsection_id": "31.6", "subsection_index": 5, "total_subsections": 23, "updated": "2024-04-06T00:00:00Z", "url": "https://www.justice.gov.uk/courts/procedure-rules/civil/rules/part31"}, {"category": "Civil Procedure Rules and Practice Directions", "citation": "31.7, Disclosure and Inspection of Documents, Part 31", "content": "31.7

(1) When giving standard disclosure, a party is required to make a reasonable search for documents falling within rule 31.6(b) or (c).

(2) The factors relevant in deciding the reasonableness of a search include the following -

(a) the number of documents involved;

(b) the nature and complexity of the proceedings;

(c) the ease and expense of retrieval of any particular document; and

(d) the significance of any document which is likely to be located during the search.

(3) Where a party has not searched for a category or class of document on the grounds that to do so would be unreasonable, he must state this in his disclosure statement and identify the category or class of document.

(Rule 31.10 makes provision for a disclosure statement)

