Disclosure of copies", "filepath": "Disclosure and Inspection of Documents", "groups": [], "id": "Part_31___Disclosure_and_Inspection_of_Documents_subsection_7", "is_subsection": true, "oids": [], "original_doc_id": "Part_31___Disclosure_and_Inspection_of_Documents", "reranker_score": 2.61181378364563, "score": 0.02460360899567604, "sourcefile": "Part 31", "sourcepage": "Disclosure and Inspection of Documents", "storageUrl": "https://www.justice.gov.uk/courts/procedure-rules/civil/rules/part31", "storageurl": "https://www.justice.gov.uk/courts/procedure-rules/civil/rules/part31", "subsection_id": "31.8", "subsection_index": 7, "total_subsections": 23, "updated": "2024-04-06T00:00:00Z", "url": "https://www.justice.gov.uk/courts/procedure-rules/civil/rules/part31"}, {"category": "Civil Procedure Rules and Practice Directions", "citation": "31.9, Disclosure and Inspection of Documents, Part 31", "content": "31.9

(1) A party need not disclose more than one copy of a document.

(2) A copy of a document that contains a modification, obliteration or other marking or feature -

(a) on which a party intends to rely; or

(b) which adversely affects his own case or another party's case or supports another party's case;

shall be treated as a separate document.

(Rule 31.4 sets out the meaning of a copy of a document)

