Specific disclosure or inspection", "filepath": "Disclosure and Inspection of Documents", "groups": [], "id": "Part_31___Disclosure_and_Inspection_of_Documents_subsection_10", "is_subsection": true, "oids": [], "original_doc_id": "Part_31___Disclosure_and_Inspection_of_Documents", "reranker_score": 2.61181378364563, "score": 0.02460360899567604, "sourcefile": "Part 31", "sourcepage": "Disclosure and Inspection of Documents", "storageUrl": "https://www.justice.gov.uk/courts/procedure-rules/civil/rules/part31", "storageurl": "https://www.justice.gov.uk/courts/procedure-rules/civil/rules/part31", "subsection_id": "31.11", "subsection_index": 10, "total_subsections": 23, "updated": "2024-04-06T00:00:00Z", "url": "https://www.justice.gov.uk/courts/procedure-rules/civil/rules/part31"}, {"category": "Civil Procedure Rules and Practice Directions", "citation": "31.12, Disclosure and Inspection of Documents, Part 31", "content": "31.12

(1) The court may make an order for specific disclosure or specific inspection.

(2) An order for specific disclosure is an order that a party must do one or more of the following things -

(a) disclose documents or classes of documents specified in the order;

(b) carry out a search to the extent stated in the order;

(c) disclose any documents located as a result of that search.

(3) An order for specific inspection is an order that a party permit inspection of a document referred to in rule 31.3(2).

(Rule 31.3(2) allows a party to state in his disclosure statement that he will not permit inspection of a document on the grounds that it would be disproportionate to do so)

