Protocol (p. 14), Technology and Construction Court Guide", "6": "2.7, Section 2. Pre-Action Protocol and conduct, 2.6 Consequences of Non-Compliance with the Protocol (p. 14), Technology and Construction Court Guide", "7": "3.1, The Courts Case Management Powers, Part 3", "8": "3.1, The Courts Case Management Powers, Part 3", "9": "3.2, The Courts Case Management Powers, Part 3"}, "data_points": {"images": null, "text": [{"category": "Technology and Construction Court", "citation": "2.6, Section 2. Pre-Action Protocol and conduct, 2.6 Consequences of Non-Compliance with the Protocol (p. 14), Technology and Construction Court Guide", "content": "2.6.1 There can often be a complaint that one or other party has not complied with the Protocol. The Court will consider any such complaints once proceedings have been commenced. If the Court finds that the claimant has not complied with one part of the Protocol, then the Court may stay the proceedings until the steps set out in the Protocol have been taken or impose such other conditions as the court thinks appropriate pursuant to CPR 3.1(2).", "filepath": "Section 2. Pre-Action Protocol and conduct, 2.6 Consequences of Non-Compliance with the Protocol (p. 14)", "groups": [], "id": "section_2_pre_action_protocol_and_conduct_26_consequences_of_non_compliance_with_the_protocol_p_14_subsection_0", "is_subsection": true, "oids": [], "original_doc_id": "section_2_pre_action_protocol_and_conduct_26_consequences_of_non_compliance_with_the_protocol_p_14", "reranker_score": 2.942888021469116, "score": 0.03229166567325592, "sourcefile": "Technology and Construction Court Guide", "sourcepage": "Section 2. Pre-Action Protocol and conduct, 2.6 Consequences of Non-Compliance with the Protocol (p. 14)", "storageUrl": "https://www.judiciary.uk/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/The-Technology-and-Construction-Court-Guide.pdf", "storageurl": "https://www.judiciary.uk/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/The-Technology-and-Construction-Court-Guide.pdf", "subsection_id": "2.6", "subsection_index": 0, "total_subsections": 6, "updated": "2022-10-01T00:00:00Z", "url": "https://www.judiciary.uk/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/The-Technology-and-Construction-Court-Guide.pdf"}, {"category": "Civil Procedure Rules and Practice Directions", "citation": "2.6, Section 2. Pre-Action Protocol and conduct, 2.6 Consequences of Non-Compliance with the Protocol (p. 14), Technology and Construction Court Guide", "content": "2.6.2 The Practice Direction in respect of Protocols (section C of volume 1 of the White Book) makes plain that the Court may make adverse costs orders against a party who has failed to comply with the Protocol. The Court will exercise any sanctions available with the object of placing the innocent party in a position no worse than if there had been compliance with the Protocol.", "filepath": "Section 2. Pre-Action Protocol and conduct, 2.6 Consequences of Non-Compliance with the Protocol (p. 14)", "groups": [], "id": "section_2_pre_action_protocol_and_conduct_26_consequences_of_non_compliance_with_the_protocol_p_14_subsection_1", "is_subsection": true, "oids": [], "original_doc_id": "section_2_pre_action_protocol_and_conduct_26_consequences_of_non_compliance_with_the_protocol_p_14", "reranker_score": 2.942888021469116, "score": 0.03229166567325592, "sourcefile": "Part 3", "sourcepage": "The Courts Case Management Powers", "storageUrl": "https://www.judiciary.uk/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/The-Technology-and-Construction-Court-Guide.pdf", "storageurl": "https://www.justice.gov.uk/courts/procedure-rules/civil/rules/part03", "subsection_id": "2.6", "subsection_index": 1, "total_subsections": 6, "updated": "2023-09-05T00:00:00Z", "url": "https://www.judiciary.uk/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/The-Technology-and-Construction-Court-Guide.pdf"}, {"category": "Civil Procedure Rules and Practice Directions", "citation": "2.6, Section 2. Pre-Action Protocol and conduct, 2.6 Consequences of Non-Compliance with the Protocol (p. 14), Technology and Construction Court Guide", "content": "2.6.3 The court is unlikely to be concerned with minor infringements of the Protocol or to engage in lengthy debates as to the precise quality of the information provided by one party to the other during the Protocol stages. The court will principally be concerned to ensure that, as a result of the Protocol stage, each party to any subsequent litigation has a clear understanding of the nature of the case that it has to meet at the commencement of those proceedings.", "filepath": "Section 2. Pre-Action Protocol and conduct, 2.6 Consequences of Non-Compliance with the Protocol (p. 14)", "groups": [], "id": "section_2_pre_action_protocol_and_conduct_26_consequences_of_non_compliance_with_the_protocol_p_14_subsection_2", "is_subsection": true, "oids": [], "original_doc_id": "section_2_pre_action_protocol_and_conduct_26_consequences_of_non_compliance_with_the_protocol_p_14", "reranker_score": 2.942888021469116, "score": 0.03229166567325592, "sourcefile": "Part 45", "sourcepage": "Fixed Costs", "storageUrl": "https://www.judiciary.uk/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/The-Technology-and-Construction-Court-Guide.pdf", "storageurl": "https://www.justice.gov.uk/courts/procedure-rules/civil/rules/part45-fixed-costs", "subsection_id": "2.6", "subsection_index": 2, "total_subsections": 6, "updated": "2024-04-06T00:00:00Z", "url": "https://www.judiciary.uk/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/The-Technology-and-Construction-Court-Guide.pdf"}, {"category": "Technology and Construction Court", "citation": "2.7, Section 2. Pre-Action Protocol and conduct, 2.6 Consequences of Non-Compliance with the Protocol (p. 14), Technology and Construction Court Guide", "content": "2.7 Costs of Compliance with the Protocol.", "filepath": "Section 2. Pre-Action Protocol and conduct, 2.6 Consequences of Non-Compliance with the Protocol (p. 14)", "groups": [], "id": "section_2_pre_action_protocol_and_conduct_26_consequences_of_non_compliance_with_the_protocol_p_14_subsection_3", "is_subsection": true, "oids": [], "original_doc_id": "section_2_pre_action_protocol_and_conduct_26_consequences_of_non_compliance_with_the_protocol_p_14", "reranker_score": 2.942888021469116, "score": 0.03229166567325592, "sourcefile": "Technology and Construction Court Guide", "sourcepage": "Section 2. Pre-Action Protocol and conduct, 2.6 Consequences of Non-Compliance with the Protocol (p. 14)", "storageUrl": "https://www.judiciary.uk/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/The-Technology-and-Construction-Court-Guide.pdf", "storageurl": "https://www.judiciary.uk/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/The-Technology-and-Construction-Court-Guide.pdf", "subsection_id": "2.7", "subsection_index": 3, "total_subsections": 6, "updated": "2022-10-01T00:00:00Z", "url": "https://www.judiciary.uk/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/The-Technology-and-Construction-Court-Guide.pdf"}, {"category": "Technology and Construction Court", "citation": "2.7, Section 2. Pre-Action Protocol and conduct, 2.6 Consequences of Non-Compliance with the Protocol (p. 14), Technology and Construction Court Guide", "content": "2.7.1 If compliance with the Protocol results in settlement, the costs incurred will not be recoverable from the paying party, unless this is specifically agreed.", "filepath": "Section 2. Pre-Action Protocol and conduct, 2.6 Consequences of Non-Compliance with the Protocol (p. 14)", "groups": [], "id": "section_2_pre_action_protocol_and_conduct_26_consequences_of_non_compliance_with_the_protocol_p_14_subsection_4", "is_subsection": true, "oids": [], "original_doc_id": "section_2_pre_action_protocol_and_conduct_26_consequences_of_non_compliance_with_the_protocol_p_14", "reranker_score": 2.942888021469116, "score": 0.03229166567325592, "sourcefile": "Technology and Construction Court Guide", "sourcepage": "Section 2. Pre-Action Protocol and conduct, 2.6 Consequences of Non-Compliance with the Protocol (p. 14)", "storageUrl": "https://www.judiciary.uk/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/The-Technology-and-Construction-Court-Guide.pdf", "storageurl": "https://www.judiciary.uk/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/The-Technology-and-Construction-Court-Guide.pdf", "subsection_id": "2.7", "subsection_index": 4, "total_subsections": 6, "updated": "2022-10-01T00:00:00Z", "url": "https://www.judiciary.uk/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/The-Technology-and-Construction-Court-Guide.pdf"}, {"category": "Technology and Construction Court", "citation": "2.7, Section 2. Pre-Action Protocol and conduct, 2.6 Consequences of Non-Compliance with the Protocol (p. 14), Technology and Construction Court Guide", "content": "2.7.2 If compliance with the Protocol does not result in settlement, then the costs of the exercise cannot be recovered as costs, unless:

a) those costs fall within the principles stated by Sir Robert Megarry V-C in Re Gibson's Settlement Trusts [1981] Ch 179; or

b) the steps taken in compliance with the Protocol can properly be attributable to the conduct of the action: see the judgment of Coulson J in Roundstone Nurseries v Stephenson [2009] EWHC 1431 (TCC) where he held at [48]: ". . . as a matter of principle, it seems to me that costs incurred during the Pre-Action Protocol process may, in principle, be recoverable as costs incidental to the litigation: see McGlinn v. Waltham (No. 1) [2005] 3 All ER 1126".

